post_text:
Amazing story about one of our amazing students! (written with permission from mom!)
I just wanted to send a quick pic of what Joe has been up to. He saved money last year and bought a 3D printer. He was able to create game pieces (which PTAA allowed him to join a game club- huge thank you to the PTAA staff -specifically Mr Sanford for supervising this activity)
PTAA’s STEM program, robotics program and 3D printer gave Joe the idea to create his own 3D printer and projects and now he is printing with these ear guards for a face masks company!
I know sometimes you all might feel disconnected from the kids you teach but, here is proof that your hard work and dedication towards education has influenced and lifted my son up to reach his potential.
We are so proud of you Joe and all of our kids. Thanks Mom for sharing!

Good afternoon PTAA family! We hope you are all doing well.
Wanted to remind you that we will not have school Friday 4/10 or Monday 4/13. However, we will be on campus Monday 4/13 to drop off/pick up packets. We will be there from 9am-5:30pm. If you prefer working on Google Classroom, you do not need to pick up packets!

Heather Roney is with David Freddie Callander.
April 3 at 10:00 AM ·

Quinn answered a request from the local hospitals for help with creating more “ear guards” to help take the pressure off health care workers ears from wearing masks all day. He got busy on his 3D printer and has been turning out dozens of ear guards to donate.
#ScoutsDoThings @scoutscanada

Edit: Due to the unbelievable response we have decided to post the link to the file we are using. https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:4249113

We need more volunteers to fire up their 3D printers and donate these ear guards to hospitals and medical professionals!

post_text:
3/31
Extended Closure until May 4th
Texas Gov. Greg Abbott has ordered the state’s schools to remain closed until May 4th in the continuing effort to slow the spread of the new coronavirus.
PTAA campuses will remain closed until at least Monday, May 4. We are coordinating with other school districts in the county and will reassess the week of April 27th to make any decisions on whether there is a need to extend the suspension further.
PTAA schools have already shifted to remote learning. The learning varies by campuses and consists of online instruction and offline instruction using printed activity packets.
This is a quickly changing situation, and we will continue to monitor information, will assess conditions throughout the week, and will provide the next update the week of
April 27th via our website and email.
Thank you for your support and cooperation as we ensure that all members of the community in PTAA stay safe and healthy.
Shubham Pandey
PTAA Superintendent

post_text:
Families-
Just breathe. We are in this with you. We know your kids. We know which ones are perfectionists and stressing about getting everything right. We know which ones are doing everything with no questions asked. We know which kids need us standing over them to get their work completed. We know these kids. We love these kids. We will continue pushing each kid to meet their maximum potential while navigating through these hard times. Please remind your kids to just breathe and do their work. We know what they are capable of doing!

WEATHER UPDATE:
It’s that time of year again! As you may have heard, meteorologists are forecasting the possibility of a wintry mix affecting Wednesday morning. Please note, the forecast is constantly evolving. Keeping the safety of our students, families and staff in mind, we are monitoring the weather conditions and will remain in touch with emergency management and local officials.

Parents and staff will be notified ONLY if there is a school cancellation or delay by 6am Wednesday morning. If you are not notified, we will have school as scheduled.

Please make sure you are a part of the campus remind group. Remind code is: @egkfk6

Mesquite Oates Campus is currently asking for donations of an unwrapped toy by next Tuesday for the SANTA COP TOY DRIVE.
The Mesquite Police distribute the toys to children who are Mesquite residents. This is special because it gives our students a way to "pay it forward" and do their part to build a positive community where they live and/or attend school.

Toys don't have to be expensive. Stuffed animals, Matchbox Cars, small dolls, Lego blocks, books, puzzles, are all examples of things students can bring.

post_text:
It is almost that time!! School is starting Monday!!! We will open our doors at 7:15. Parents need your help with traffic flow. Enter on Oates through the swing gate and move into two lanes through campus. High school students will enter through the front doors and middle school students will enter through the second foyer (where you entered for orientation). Please have your child exit the car quickly and safely then enter the building. We are asking that parents not walk students in as we do not have enough parking.
Students are expected to be in formal dress-normal Monday attire. If you ordered a blazer and it has not come in yet, we will make note of that.
Remember students must be in their classrooms by 8am. If they are not in their classrooms, they are tardy.
Supplies and first day packets will be turned into their first period teacher. If you did not get a packet, we will send them home Monday.
I look forward to meeting everyone! Enjoy your weekend

post_text:
Dear Community,

STAAR scores have been released. See the information below for instructions of how to access your child's scores.

Go to the Texas Assessment Data Portal http://texasassessment.com
1. Select FIND MY UNIQUE STUDENT ACCESS CODE.
2. Parents will then be prompted to enter in:
-Student's First Name,
-Social Security Number or S-Number (State issued ID Number), and
-Date of Birth.

Estimada Comunidad,

Las calificaciones del STAAR han sido publicadas. Consulte la información a continuación para obtener instrucciones sobre cómo acceder a las calificaciones de su hijo/a.

Vaya al portal de datos de evaluación de Texas http://texasassessment.com y haga clic en ESPAÑOL
1. Seleccione BUSCAR CODIGO DE ACCESO (FIND MY UNIQUE STUDENT ACCESS CODE)

Dear Community,

STAAR scores have been released. See the information below for instructions of how to access your child's scores.

Go to the Texas Assessment Data Portal http://texasassessment.com
1. Select FIND MY UNIQUE STUDENT ACCESS CODE.
2. Parents will then be prompted to enter in:
-Student's First Name,
-Social Security Number or S-Number (State issued ID Number), and
-Date of Birth.

Estimada Comunidad,

Las calificaciones del STAAR han sido publicadas. Consulte la información a continuación para obtener instrucciones sobre cómo acceder a las calificaciones de su hijo/a.

Vaya al portal de datos de evaluación de Texas http://texasassessment.com y haga clic en ESPAÑOL
1. Seleccione BUSCAR CODIGO DE ACCESO (FIND MY UNIQUE STUDENT ACCESS CODE)
2. A los padres se les pedirá que pongan:
-Nombre del estudiante,
-Número de seguridad social o número S (Número de identificación emitido por el estado), y
-Fecha de nacimiento.
